<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-391-010  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 391 010.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  June 26 1989 n544 pT5(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Integration: the '90s challenge.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Carver, Bob.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Driven by the evolving needs of users unable to master the dozensof tools and systems required to guide a design from conception tomanufacture, the big challenge for the design automation industrywill be to develop an integrated design environment during the1990s.andP;  The basic building block of this evolution will be aframework encompassing agreed-upon industry standards supportingreal-time data sharing.andP;  Both integrated circuit and systemsdesigners have been limited by a process that has becomeincreasingly fragmented.andP;  Top-down design methodologies willcharacterize the 1990s design environment, which will include afriendly user interface, a common database andinformation-sharing, multiple design methodologies and tools andan open systems approach.andP;  The typical top-down design strategywill involve behavioral specification, functional decomposition,physical realization and validation.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Integrated SystemsTrendsComputer-Aided EngineeringAutomationStandardizationComputer-Aided Design.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Design framework architecture. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>